  "questions": [
    {
      "question": "In $\\triangle OPA$, $O$ is the centre of a circle and $PA$ is a tangent at point $A$. If the radius of the circle $OA = 6$ $\\text{cm}$ and the distance $OP = 10$ $\\text{cm}$, what is the length of the tangent $PA$?",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify that a tangent to a circle is perpendicular to the radius at the point of contact, so $\\angle OAP = 90^\\circ$.",
          "Observe that $\\triangle OAP$ is a right-angled triangle with hypotenuse $OP = 10$ $\\text{cm}$ and one leg $OA = 6$ $\\text{cm}$.",
          "Apply the Pythagoras theorem: $OP^2 = OA^2 + PA^2$.",
          "Substitute the values: $10^2 = 6^2 + PA^2 \\Rightarrow 100 = 36 + PA^2$.",
          "Solve for $PA$: $PA^2 = 100 - 36 = 64$, so $PA = 8$ $\\text{cm}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$OA \\perp PA \\Rightarrow \\angle OAP = 90^\\circ \\\\ OP^2 = OA^2 + PA^2 \\\\ 10^2 = 6^2 + PA^2 \\\\ 100 = 36 + PA^2 \\\\ PA^2 = 64 \\\\ PA = 8 \\text{ cm}$"
      },
